</div><div class="info-panel__citations info-panel__item"><a href="#tab-citations" class="btn btn--inverse btn--slim" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="View Citations" aria-label="View Citations"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-format_quote"></i></a></div><div class="info-panel__formats info-panel__item"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="Go to purchase options" aria-label="Go to purchase options"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="link-text">Get Access</span></a></div></div></div></div></header><div data-core-nav="header" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-nav-wrapper core-container" aria-label="Article navigation"><div><button aria-controls="article_sections_menu" aria-expanded="false" aria-label="Toggle section navigation menu"><i class="icon-list" aria-hidden="true"></i><span>Contents</span></button><nav id="article_sections_menu" aria-label="Contents" data-core-nav="article"><ul><li><a href="#abstract">Abstract</a></li><li><a href="#core-sec-figures">Figures</a></li><li><a href="#bibliography">References</a></li></ul></nav></div><nav id="article_collateral_menu"><ul class="collateral-pill" data-core-nav="collateral"><li><a href="#core-collateral-info" aria-controls="core-collateral-info" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Information & Authors" title="Information & Authors" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-info"></i><span class="sr-only">Information & Authors</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-metrics" aria-controls="core-collateral-metrics" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Metrics & Citations" title="Metrics & Citations" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-metrics"></i><span class="sr-only">Metrics & Citations</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-controls="core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Get Access" title="Get Access" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="sr-only">Get Access</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-references" aria-controls="core-collateral-references" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="References" title="References" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-references"></i><span class="sr-only">References</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-figures" aria-controls="core-collateral-figures" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Figures" title="Figures" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-photo"></i><span class="sr-only">Figures</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-tables" aria-controls="core-collateral-tables" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Tables" title="Tables" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-table"></i><span class="sr-only">Tables</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-media" aria-controls="core-collateral-media" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Media" title="Media" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-play-circle-filled"></i><span class="sr-only">Media</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-share" aria-controls="core-collateral-share" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Share" title="Share" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-share"></i><span class="sr-only">Share</span></a></li></ul></nav></div></div><div data-core-wrapper="content"><div id="abstracts" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Abstract</h2><div role="paragraph">Granulomatous diseases have a varied etiology that includes autoimmune, infectious, idiopathic, and hereditary causes. The unifying factor in these diseases is the formation of granulomas, which histologically are mononuclear inflammatory cells or macrophages surrounded by lymphocytes. Granulomatous diseases often have systemic manifestations that affect organs throughout the body. Granulomatous diseases with head and neck manifestations include granulomatosis with polyangiitis, Churg-Strauss syndrome, Behçet disease, chronic granulomatous disease, and sarcoidosis. Infectious causes include tuberculosis, cat-scratch disease, syphilis, leprosy, actinomycosis, rhinoscleroma, and fungal infections. In the head and neck, granulomatous disease may affect the orbits, sinonasal cavities, salivary glands, aerodigestive tract, temporal bone, or skull base. Imaging findings include sinonasal opacification, ocular and other soft-tissue masses, osseous erosion, airway narrowing, lymphadenopathy, and salivary gland infiltration. Vascular involvement may also be evident, with displacement, narrowing, or occlusion of arteries and veins. Some radiologic findings of granulomatous processes have a considerable overlap with findings of malignancy, and a radiologic differential diagnosis inclusive of both is critical to avoid incorrect clinical treatment. Without the benefit of a prior clinical diagnosis, laboratory findings, or suggestive clinical signs and symptoms, granulomatous diseases may be difficult to differentiate radiologically. Although individual granulomatous diseases may have overlapping findings at imaging, certain radiologic findings should prompt the inclusion of granulomatous diseases in the differential diagnosis, thus facilitating appropriate clinical management.</div><div role="paragraph">©RSNA, 2014</div></section></div></div><section id="bodymatter" data-extent="bodymatter" property="articleBody" typeof="Text"><div class="core-container"><section aria-labelledby="denial-block-title" class="denial-block "><h2 id="denial-block-title" class="denial-block__title">Get full access to this article</h2><p class="denial-block__text">View all available purchase options and get full access to this article.</p><div class="denial-block__cta"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span>Get Access</span></a></div><footer class="denial-block__footer"><span>Already a Subscriber? </span><span>Sign in as an </span><a href="/action/showLogin?redirectUri=/doi/10.1148/rg.345130068">individual</a><span> or via your </span><a href="/action/ssostart?uri=/doi/10.1148/rg.345130068">institution</a></footer></section></div></section><section id="backmatter" data-extent="backmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="core-sec-figures" data-type="figures"><h2>Figures</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130068/asset/images/large/rg.345130068.fig1a.jpeg" height="787" width="789" aria-labelledby="fig1a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1a</span> Sarcoidosis in a 26-year-old woman who presented with a nasal mass. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced computed tomographic (CT) image shows mildly enhancing polypoid lesions (arrow) in the anterior nasal cavity along the nasal septum and opacification of the right maxillary sinus (<b>*</b>). <b>(b)</b> Axial T2-weighted magnetic resonance (MR) image shows soft-tissue lesions (arrow) with heterogeneous signal intensity filling the nasal cavities bilaterally, as well as right maxillary sinus opacification (<b>*</b>). Biopsy of the nasal polypoid lesion revealed noncaseating granulomas, consistent with sarcoidosis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130068&amp;id=fig1a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130068/asset/images/large/rg.345130068.fig1b.jpeg" height="787" width="789" aria-labelledby="fig1b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1b</span> Sarcoidosis in a 26-year-old woman who presented with a nasal mass. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced computed tomographic (CT) image shows mildly enhancing polypoid lesions (arrow) in the anterior nasal cavity along the nasal septum and opacification of the right maxillary sinus (<b>*</b>). <b>(b)</b> Axial T2-weighted magnetic resonance (MR) image shows soft-tissue lesions (arrow) with heterogeneous signal intensity filling the nasal cavities bilaterally, as well as right maxillary sinus opacification (<b>*</b>). Biopsy of the nasal polypoid lesion revealed noncaseating granulomas, consistent with sarcoidosis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130068&amp;id=fig1b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130068/asset/images/large/rg.345130068.fig2a.jpeg" height="836" width="798" aria-labelledby="fig2a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2a</span> GPA in an 18-year-old woman who presented with epistaxis and progression of chronic sinusitis. Axial nonenhanced CT images through the maxillary sinuses show the progression of right maxillary sinus opacification (<b>*</b>) over 3 years: at presentation <b>(a)</b>, with worsened symptoms 1 year later <b>(b)</b>, and 3 years after presentation <b>(c)</b>. Note the evolution of sclerosis and contraction of the sinus walls. Progressive turbinate and nasal septal erosion is also seen (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130068&amp;id=fig2a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130068/asset/images/large/rg.345130068.fig2b.jpeg" height="809" width="780" aria-labelledby="fig2b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2b</span> GPA in an 18-year-old woman who presented with epistaxis and progression of chronic sinusitis. Axial nonenhanced CT images through the maxillary sinuses show the progression of right maxillary sinus opacification (<b>*</b>) over 3 years: at presentation <b>(a)</b>, with worsened symptoms 1 year later <b>(b)</b>, and 3 years after presentation <b>(c)</b>. Note the evolution of sclerosis and contraction of the sinus walls. Progressive turbinate and nasal septal erosion is also seen (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130068&amp;id=fig2b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130068/asset/images/large/rg.345130068.fig2c.jpeg" height="809" width="796" aria-labelledby="fig2c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2c</span> GPA in an 18-year-old woman who presented with epistaxis and progression of chronic sinusitis. Axial nonenhanced CT images through the maxillary sinuses show the progression of right maxillary sinus opacification (<b>*</b>) over 3 years: at presentation <b>(a)</b>, with worsened symptoms 1 year later <b>(b)</b>, and 3 years after presentation <b>(c)</b>. Note the evolution of sclerosis and contraction of the sinus walls. Progressive turbinate and nasal septal erosion is also seen (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130068&amp;id=fig2c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130068/asset/images/large/rg.345130068.fig3.jpeg" height="758" width="800" aria-labelledby="fig3" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3</span> GPA in a 67-year-old woman who presented with multiple cranial nerve impairments. Coronal T2-weighted MR image shows diffuse low signal intensity in the nasal septum, turbinates, and paranasal sinus walls (arrows) due to chronic inflammation and sclerosis. Biopsy of the nasopharynx revealed GPA.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130068&amp;id=fig3">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130068/asset/images/large/rg.345130068.fig4.jpeg" height="815" width="800" aria-labelledby="fig4" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4</span> Churg-Strauss syndrome with sinusitis and sinonasal polyposis in a 41-year-old man who presented with headache and nasal obstruction. Axial nonenhanced CT image shows bilateral maxillary polypoid mucosal thickening admixed with high-attenuation material suggestive of inspissated mucus (<b>*</b>). Polypoid lesions are seen in the nasal cavity (arrow), with adjacent nasal septal perforation (arrowhead).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130068&amp;id=fig4">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130068/asset/images/large/rg.345130068.fig5.jpeg" height="877" width="800" aria-labelledby="fig5" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5</span> GPA in a 47-year-old man who presented with left orbital pain. Coronal T2-weighted MR image shows a soft-tissue masslike lesion invading the left orbital floor (arrow). Note the large defect of the nasal septum (<b>*</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130068&amp;id=fig5">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130068/asset/images/large/rg.345130068.fig6.jpeg" height="801" width="800" aria-labelledby="fig6" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6</span> Sarcoidosis in a 38-year-old woman who presented with left eye pain and decreased vision. Axial contrast-enhanced fat-suppressed T1-weighted MR image shows an infiltrative left retrobulbar superior orbital lesion (arrow) with diffuse enhancement. The lesion involves the extraocular muscles and lacrimal gland.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130068&amp;id=fig6">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130068/asset/images/large/rg.345130068.fig7.jpeg" height="800" width="800" aria-labelledby="fig7" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7</span> GPA in a 30-year-old woman with a history of enucleation of the left eye due to a pseudotumor 12 years earlier. Coronal contrast-enhanced fat-suppressed T1-weighted MR image shows diffuse enhancement of the left orbit, which is partially imaged (arrow). Note the associated dural enhancement at the left anterior skull base and along the superior falx (arrowheads).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130068&amp;id=fig7">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130068/asset/images/large/rg.345130068.fig8a.jpeg" height="759" width="785" aria-labelledby="fig8a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8a</span> GPA in a 54-year-old man who presented with hemoptysis and diplopia. Axial T2-weighted <b>(a)</b> and contrast-enhanced fat-suppressed T1-weighted <b>(b)</b> MR images show bilateral lesions at the orbital apex (arrows) that demonstrate low T2 signal intensity in <b>a</b> and avid enhancement in <b>b</b>, with the left lesion larger than the right lesion. Note the abnormal flow voids in the left temporal region, findings consistent with a known arteriovenous malformation.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130068&amp;id=fig8a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130068/asset/images/large/rg.345130068.fig8b.jpeg" height="759" width="788" aria-labelledby="fig8b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8b</span> GPA in a 54-year-old man who presented with hemoptysis and diplopia. Axial T2-weighted <b>(a)</b> and contrast-enhanced fat-suppressed T1-weighted <b>(b)</b> MR images show bilateral lesions at the orbital apex (arrows) that demonstrate low T2 signal intensity in <b>a</b> and avid enhancement in <b>b</b>, with the left lesion larger than the right lesion. Note the abnormal flow voids in the left temporal region, findings consistent with a known arteriovenous malformation.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130068&amp;id=fig8b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130068/asset/images/large/rg.345130068.fig9.jpeg" height="876" width="800" aria-labelledby="fig9" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9</span> Sarcoidosis in a 38-year-old woman who presented with bilateral exophthalmos. Coronal contrast-enhanced fat-suppressed T1-weighted MR image shows homogeneous enhancement in the enlarged lacrimal glands bilaterally (arrows). Dural enhancement is seen in the right frontal region (arrowhead).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130068&amp;id=fig9">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130068/asset/images/large/rg.345130068.fig10a.jpeg" height="786" width="788" aria-labelledby="fig10a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10a</span> GPA in a 56-year-old woman who presented with disturbed consciousness. <b>(a)</b> Axial T2-weighted MR image shows edema with sulcal effacement in the right temporal lobe (arrow). Note the opacification of the right mastoid air cells (arrowhead). <b>(b)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted MR image shows enhancement of the right mastoid air cells (arrow) and thickened dura (arrowhead).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130068&amp;id=fig10a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130068/asset/images/large/rg.345130068.fig10b.jpeg" height="786" width="786" aria-labelledby="fig10b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10b</span> GPA in a 56-year-old woman who presented with disturbed consciousness. <b>(a)</b> Axial T2-weighted MR image shows edema with sulcal effacement in the right temporal lobe (arrow). Note the opacification of the right mastoid air cells (arrowhead). <b>(b)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted MR image shows enhancement of the right mastoid air cells (arrow) and thickened dura (arrowhead).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130068&amp;id=fig10b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130068/asset/images/large/rg.345130068.fig11a.jpeg" height="789" width="788" aria-labelledby="fig11a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11a</span> LCH in a 1-year-old boy who presented with recurrent otitis media. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows a heterogeneously enhancing lesion centered in the right mastoid process (<b>*</b>). <b>(b)</b> Axial CT image (bone window) shows osseous destruction in the mastoid process of the right temporal bone (arrow). The right mastoid air cells and tympanic cavity are completely opacified (arrowhead). Partial opacification of the left mastoid air cells and tympanic cavity is also seen.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130068&amp;id=fig11a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130068/asset/images/large/rg.345130068.fig11b.jpeg" height="789" width="788" aria-labelledby="fig11b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11b</span> LCH in a 1-year-old boy who presented with recurrent otitis media. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows a heterogeneously enhancing lesion centered in the right mastoid process (<b>*</b>). <b>(b)</b> Axial CT image (bone window) shows osseous destruction in the mastoid process of the right temporal bone (arrow). The right mastoid air cells and tympanic cavity are completely opacified (arrowhead). Partial opacification of the left mastoid air cells and tympanic cavity is also seen.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130068&amp;id=fig11b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130068/asset/images/large/rg.345130068.fig12.jpeg" height="952" width="800" aria-labelledby="fig12" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12</span> Tuberculous meningitis in a 31-year-old woman with miliary tuberculosis who presented with altered mental status. Axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted MR image shows leptomeningeal enhancement, particularly along the basal meninges (arrows).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130068&amp;id=fig12">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130068/asset/images/large/rg.345130068.fig13a.jpeg" height="788" width="788" aria-labelledby="fig13a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13a</span> LCH in a 43-year-old man who presented with diabetes insipidus. Sagittal nonenhanced <b>(a)</b> and contrast-enhanced <b>(b)</b> T1-weighted MR images show a bulbous homogeneously enhancing mass involving the hypothalamus and pituitary stalk (arrow). The posterior bright spot of the pituitary gland is not seen (arrowhead in <b>a</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130068&amp;id=fig13a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130068/asset/images/large/rg.345130068.fig13b.jpeg" height="788" width="788" aria-labelledby="fig13b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13b</span> LCH in a 43-year-old man who presented with diabetes insipidus. Sagittal nonenhanced <b>(a)</b> and contrast-enhanced <b>(b)</b> T1-weighted MR images show a bulbous homogeneously enhancing mass involving the hypothalamus and pituitary stalk (arrow). The posterior bright spot of the pituitary gland is not seen (arrowhead in <b>a</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130068&amp;id=fig13b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130068/asset/images/large/rg.345130068.fig14a.jpeg" height="788" width="788" aria-labelledby="fig14a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14a</span> GPA in a 67-year-old man who presented with multiple cranial nerve impairments. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial T1-weighted <b>(a)</b> and T2-weighted <b>(b)</b> MR images demonstrate soft-tissue thickening in the nasopharynx (arrows) and opacification of the mastoid air cells bilaterally. <b>(c)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced fat-suppressed T1-weighted MR image shows abnormal diffuse enhancement of the mucosa, torus tubarius, eustachian tubes (arrows), and longus colli muscles (<b>*</b>) that extends to the jugular foramina bilaterally (arrowheads).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130068&amp;id=fig14a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130068/asset/images/large/rg.345130068.fig14b.jpeg" height="786" width="788" aria-labelledby="fig14b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14b</span> GPA in a 67-year-old man who presented with multiple cranial nerve impairments. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial T1-weighted <b>(a)</b> and T2-weighted <b>(b)</b> MR images demonstrate soft-tissue thickening in the nasopharynx (arrows) and opacification of the mastoid air cells bilaterally. <b>(c)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced fat-suppressed T1-weighted MR image shows abnormal diffuse enhancement of the mucosa, torus tubarius, eustachian tubes (arrows), and longus colli muscles (<b>*</b>) that extends to the jugular foramina bilaterally (arrowheads).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130068&amp;id=fig14b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130068/asset/images/large/rg.345130068.fig14c.jpeg" height="800" width="800" aria-labelledby="fig14c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14c</span> GPA in a 67-year-old man who presented with multiple cranial nerve impairments. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial T1-weighted <b>(a)</b> and T2-weighted <b>(b)</b> MR images demonstrate soft-tissue thickening in the nasopharynx (arrows) and opacification of the mastoid air cells bilaterally. <b>(c)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced fat-suppressed T1-weighted MR image shows abnormal diffuse enhancement of the mucosa, torus tubarius, eustachian tubes (arrows), and longus colli muscles (<b>*</b>) that extends to the jugular foramina bilaterally (arrowheads).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130068&amp;id=fig14c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130068/asset/images/large/rg.345130068.fig15.jpeg" height="800" width="800" aria-labelledby="fig15" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15</span> Sarcoidosis in a 53-year-old man who presented with a pulsatile mass in the left side of the neck. Axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted MR image shows a well-demarcated enhancing mass surrounding the left common carotid artery (arrow). Biopsy of the mass revealed sarcoidosis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130068&amp;id=fig15">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130068/asset/images/large/rg.345130068.fig16a.jpeg" height="896" width="743" aria-labelledby="fig16a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16a</span> GPA in a 41-year-old woman who presented with worsening left-sided mixed hearing loss. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted MR image shows a large defect in the left nasal cavity and ethmoid sinus (<b>*</b>), with destruction of the clivus. Diffuse enhancement of the mastoid air cells (arrow) is due to inflammation secondary to eustachian tube obstruction. <b>(b)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows extensive destruction of the nasal cavity, including a large nasal septal defect (<b>*</b>) and osseous defects involving the lateral wall of the sphenoid sinus, clivus, and left petrous apex. Note the encasement of the basilar artery (arrow). <b>(c)</b> Three-dimensional volume-rendered image from MR angiography shows severe narrowing of the basilar artery (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130068&amp;id=fig16a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130068/asset/images/large/rg.345130068.fig16b.jpeg" height="896" width="734" aria-labelledby="fig16b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16b</span> GPA in a 41-year-old woman who presented with worsening left-sided mixed hearing loss. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted MR image shows a large defect in the left nasal cavity and ethmoid sinus (<b>*</b>), with destruction of the clivus. Diffuse enhancement of the mastoid air cells (arrow) is due to inflammation secondary to eustachian tube obstruction. <b>(b)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows extensive destruction of the nasal cavity, including a large nasal septal defect (<b>*</b>) and osseous defects involving the lateral wall of the sphenoid sinus, clivus, and left petrous apex. Note the encasement of the basilar artery (arrow). <b>(c)</b> Three-dimensional volume-rendered image from MR angiography shows severe narrowing of the basilar artery (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130068&amp;id=fig16b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130068/asset/images/large/rg.345130068.fig16c.jpeg" height="838" width="799" aria-labelledby="fig16c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16c</span> GPA in a 41-year-old woman who presented with worsening left-sided mixed hearing loss. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted MR image shows a large defect in the left nasal cavity and ethmoid sinus (<b>*</b>), with destruction of the clivus. Diffuse enhancement of the mastoid air cells (arrow) is due to inflammation secondary to eustachian tube obstruction. <b>(b)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows extensive destruction of the nasal cavity, including a large nasal septal defect (<b>*</b>) and osseous defects involving the lateral wall of the sphenoid sinus, clivus, and left petrous apex. Note the encasement of the basilar artery (arrow). <b>(c)</b> Three-dimensional volume-rendered image from MR angiography shows severe narrowing of the basilar artery (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130068&amp;id=fig16c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig17a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130068/asset/images/large/rg.345130068.fig17a.jpeg" height="800" width="776" aria-labelledby="fig17a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 17a</span> Sarcoidosis in a 51-year-old woman who presented with hoarseness. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image through the nasopharynx shows enlarged adenoids (<b>*</b>). Note the heterogeneously enhancing infiltrative changes in the parotid glands bilaterally (arrows). <b>(b)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image through the larynx demonstrates heterogeneously enhancing thickened aryepiglottic folds (arrows). Biopsy of the nasopharynx revealed sarcoidosis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130068&amp;id=fig17a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig17b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130068/asset/images/large/rg.345130068.fig17b.jpeg" height="800" width="799" aria-labelledby="fig17b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 17b</span> Sarcoidosis in a 51-year-old woman who presented with hoarseness. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image through the nasopharynx shows enlarged adenoids (<b>*</b>). Note the heterogeneously enhancing infiltrative changes in the parotid glands bilaterally (arrows). <b>(b)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image through the larynx demonstrates heterogeneously enhancing thickened aryepiglottic folds (arrows). Biopsy of the nasopharynx revealed sarcoidosis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130068&amp;id=fig17b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig18a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130068/asset/images/large/rg.345130068.fig18a.jpeg" height="678" width="799" aria-labelledby="fig18a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 18a</span> Relapsing polychondritis in a 48-year-old man who presented with severe dyspnea. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows diffuse soft-tissue swelling of the larynx with laryngeal cartilage destruction (arrows). <b>(b)</b> Axial T2-weighted MR image shows mixed high and low signal intensity in the larynx (arrows), findings indicative of active inflammation and destruction of the laryngeal cartilage.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130068&amp;id=fig18a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig18b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130068/asset/images/large/rg.345130068.fig18b.jpeg" height="678" width="776" aria-labelledby="fig18b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 18b</span> Relapsing polychondritis in a 48-year-old man who presented with severe dyspnea. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows diffuse soft-tissue swelling of the larynx with laryngeal cartilage destruction (arrows). <b>(b)</b> Axial T2-weighted MR image shows mixed high and low signal intensity in the larynx (arrows), findings indicative of active inflammation and destruction of the laryngeal cartilage.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130068&amp;id=fig18b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig19a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130068/asset/images/large/rg.345130068.fig19a.jpeg" height="734" width="772" aria-labelledby="fig19a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 19a</span> Tuberculosis of the larynx in a 69-year-old man who presented with hoarseness. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows diffuse swelling and enhancement of the vocal cords (arrows). <b>(b)</b> Axial CT image at the level of the lungs shows the “tree-in-bud” appearance of the bilateral upper lobes. Biopsy of the larynx revealed tuberculosis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130068&amp;id=fig19a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig19b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130068/asset/images/large/rg.345130068.fig19b.jpeg" height="734" width="1001" aria-labelledby="fig19b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 19b</span> Tuberculosis of the larynx in a 69-year-old man who presented with hoarseness. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows diffuse swelling and enhancement of the vocal cords (arrows). <b>(b)</b> Axial CT image at the level of the lungs shows the “tree-in-bud” appearance of the bilateral upper lobes. Biopsy of the larynx revealed tuberculosis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130068&amp;id=fig19b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig20a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130068/asset/images/large/rg.345130068.fig20a.jpeg" height="788" width="788" aria-labelledby="fig20a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 20a</span> GPA in a 59-year-old man who presented with dyspnea. <b>(a)</b> Axial nonenhanced CT image shows concentric submucosal thickening in the subglottis (arrows). <b>(b)</b> Axial nonenhanced chest CT image shows mucosal thickening and stenosis of the left mainstem bronchus (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130068&amp;id=fig20a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig20b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130068/asset/images/large/rg.345130068.fig20b.jpeg" height="788" width="788" aria-labelledby="fig20b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 20b</span> GPA in a 59-year-old man who presented with dyspnea. <b>(a)</b> Axial nonenhanced CT image shows concentric submucosal thickening in the subglottis (arrows). <b>(b)</b> Axial nonenhanced chest CT image shows mucosal thickening and stenosis of the left mainstem bronchus (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130068&amp;id=fig20b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig21" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130068/asset/images/large/rg.345130068.fig21.jpeg" height="794" width="800" aria-labelledby="fig21" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 21</span> Actinomycosis in a 73-year-old man who presented with locked jaw. Axial contrast-enhanced fat-suppressed T1-weighted MR image shows infiltration and heterogeneous enhancement at the temporomandibular joint that extends to the masseter and lateral pterygoid muscles and superficial soft tissue (<b>*</b>). Note the enhancement of the right mandibular condyle (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130068&amp;id=fig21">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig22a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130068/asset/images/large/rg.345130068.fig22a.jpeg" height="847" width="786" aria-labelledby="fig22a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 22a</span> Tuberculosis in a 32-year-old man who presented with submental swelling and a left parotid mass. Axial unenhanced <b>(a)</b> and contrast-enhanced <b>(b)</b> fat-suppressed T1-weighted MR images through the parotid glands show a heterogeneously enhancing lesion (a tuberculoma) in the left parotid gland (arrow). Biopsy of a necrotic submental lymph node (not shown) revealed tuberculosis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130068&amp;id=fig22a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig22b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130068/asset/images/large/rg.345130068.fig22b.jpeg" height="847" width="790" aria-labelledby="fig22b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 22b</span> Tuberculosis in a 32-year-old man who presented with submental swelling and a left parotid mass. Axial unenhanced <b>(a)</b> and contrast-enhanced <b>(b)</b> fat-suppressed T1-weighted MR images through the parotid glands show a heterogeneously enhancing lesion (a tuberculoma) in the left parotid gland (arrow). Biopsy of a necrotic submental lymph node (not shown) revealed tuberculosis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130068&amp;id=fig22b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig23" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130068/asset/images/large/rg.345130068.fig23.jpeg" height="1006" width="800" aria-labelledby="fig23" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 23</span> Chronic granulomatous disease in a 1-year-old girl who presented with neck swelling. Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows bilateral necrotic lymphadenopathy (arrows).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130068&amp;id=fig23">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig24" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.345130068/asset/images/large/rg.345130068.fig24.jpeg" height="672" width="800" aria-labelledby="fig24" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 24</span> Tuberculosis in a 27-year-old man who presented with left-sided neck swelling. Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image shows multiple rim-enhancing low-attenuation lymph nodes in the left jugular and spinal accessory chains (arrows).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.345130068&amp;id=fig24">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div></section><section id="bibliography" role="doc-bibliography"><h2>References</h2><div role="list"><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">1.</div><div id="r1" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Kaye P. Granulomatous diseases. <em>Int J Exp Pathol</em> 2000;81(5):289–290.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1046/j.1365-2613.2000.00171.x">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/11168676/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https